{"title_page": "Halet Efendi", "text_new": "[[File:Jacques-Louis David The Coronation of Napoleon Halet Efendi detail.jpg|thumb|250px|Turbaned Ottoman ambassador Halet Efendi in ''[[The Coronation of Napoleon]]'' in 1805, by [[Jacques-Louis David]] (detail).]]\n'''Mehmet Sait Halet Efendi''' (1761\u20131822) was an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[diplomat]] and [[politician]], [[ambassador]] to [[Paris]] from 1803 to 1806<ref name=\"Mongan, p.102-103\">Mongan, p.102-103</ref> and later the favourite and [[Inner Minister]] of the [[sultan]] [[Mahmud II]].<ref>H.Tonnet</ref> He was [[ambassador]] to the court of [[Napoleon I]] until 1806,<ref>Karsh, p.14</ref> and was succeeded in this role by [[Muhib Efendi]], who was ambassador from 1806 to 1811.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cjbYxqoJyZoC&pg=PA228 by Virginia H. Aksan, ''Ottoman Wars 1700-1870: An Empire Besieged''], Longman/Pearson, 2007, p.228</ref>\n\nIn 1819 Halet Efendi brought the attention of Sultan [[Mahmud II]] to the power-grabbing activities of [[Ali Pasha of Yanina|Ali Pasha]] in Ottoman Europe. As Mahmud II sent an army against Ali Pasha, the latter responded by encouraging a rebellion against Ottoman power in [[Greece]]. These event led to the catastrophic [[Greek insurrection]] in 1821. Considered by the Sultan as contributing to the rebellion, Halet was banished from the court before being assassinated in [[Konya]], present-day Turkey, in November 1822. He was strangled and beheaded.<ref name=\"Mongan, p.102-103\"/><ref>Aksan (2007), ''Ottoman Wars'', p. 288</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Franco-Ottoman alliance]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Inari Karsh, ''Empires of the Sand: The Struggle for Mastery in the Middle East, 1789-1923,'' Harvard University Press, 2001 {{ISBN|0-674-00541-4}}\n* [[Agnes Mongan]], Miriam Stewart, Fogg Art Museum, ''David to Corot: French drawings in the Fogg Art Museum,'' Harvard University Press, 1996 {{ISBN|0-674-19320-2}}\n*Henri Tonnet, \u00ab [http://ceb.revues.org/1573 Constantinople dans quelques textes grecs de fiction aux XVIIIe et XIXe si\u00e8cles]  \u00bb, Cahiers balkaniques, 36-37 | 2008, 321\u2013328.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Efendi, Halet}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Ottoman Empire to France]]\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1822 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:19th-century diplomats]]\n[[Category:Executed people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions by the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1822 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Jacques-Louis David The Coronation of Napoleon Halet Efendi detail.jpg|thumb|250px|Turbaned Ottoman ambassador Halet Efendi in ''[[The Coronation of Napoleon]]'' in 1805, by [[Jacques-Louis David]] (detail).]]\n'''Mehmet Sait Halet Efendi''' (1761\u20131822) was an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[diplomat]] and [[politician]], [[ambassador]] to [[Paris]] from 1803 to 1806<ref name=\"Mongan, p.102-103\">Mongan, p.102-103</ref> and later the favourite and [[Inner Minister]] of the [[sultan]] [[Mahmud II]].<ref>H.Tonnet</ref> He was [[ambassador]] to the court of [[Napoleon I]] until 1806,<ref>Karsh, p.14</ref> and was succeeded in this role by [[Muhib Efendi]], who was ambassador from 1806 to 1811.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cjbYxqoJyZoC&pg=PA228 by Virginia H. Aksan, ''Ottoman Wars 1700-1870: An Empire Besieged''], Longman/Pearson, 2007, p.228</ref>\n\nIn 1819 Halet Efendi brought the attention of Sultan [[Mahmud II]] to the power-grabbing activities of [[Ali Pasha of Yanina|Ali Pasha]] in Ottoman Europe. As Mahmud II sent an army against Ali Pasha, the latter responded by encouraging a rebellion against Ottoman power in [[Greece]]. These event led to the catastrophic [[Greek insurrection]] in 1821. Considered by the Sultan as contributing to the rebellion, Halet was banished from the court before being assassinated in [[Konya]], present-day Turkey, in November 1822. He was strangled and beheaded.<ref name=\"Mongan, p.102-103\"/><ref>Aksan (2007), ''Ottoman Wars'', p. 288</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Franco-Ottoman alliance]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Inari Karsh, ''Empires of the Sand: The Struggle for Mastery in the Middle East, 1789-1923,'' Harvard University Press, 2001 {{ISBN|0-674-00541-4}}\n* [[Agnes Mongan]], Miriam Stewart, Fogg Art Museum, ''David to Corot: French drawings in the Fogg Art Museum,'' Harvard University Press, 1996 {{ISBN|0-674-19320-2}}\n*Henri Tonnet, \u00ab [http://ceb.revues.org/1573 Constantinople dans quelques textes grecs de fiction aux XVIIIe et XIXe si\u00e8cles]  \u00bb, Cahiers balkaniques, 36-37 | 2008, 321-328.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Efendi, Halet}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Ottoman Empire to France]]\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1822 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:19th-century diplomats]]\n[[Category:Executed people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions by the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1822 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 321-328 \u2192 321\u2013328", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halet_Efendi"}
